nted based on various applications that cater to the diverse needs of patients with neurological conditions. One of the primary applications is the management of intracranial pressure (ICP) in patients with severe head injuries, brain tumors, or hydrocephalus. EVDs are crucial for monitoring and controlling ICP, which is vital for preventing secondary brain damage and ensuring optimal patient outcomes. In acute care settings, such as intensive care units (ICUs) and emergency departments, EVDs are employed to provide real-time ICP measurements and facilitate the removal of excess cerebrospinal fluid (CSF). This application is particularly significant for trauma patients and those undergoing neurosurgical procedures, as precise ICP management can significantly impact recovery and prognosis. Additionally, EVDs are used in the treatment of conditions that cause abnormal CSF accumulation, such as communicating or non-communicating hydrocephalus, providing a temporary solution to manage fluid levels until a more permanent intervention can be performed.</p><p>Another key application of EVDs is in the management of post-surgical patients, particularly those recovering from brain surgery or complex neurosurgical interventions. Following such procedures, EVDs are used to monitor and manage ICP to prevent complications like brain swelling or herniation. They also play a role in the treatment of infections or hemorrhages in the brain, allowing for the continuous drainage of infected or bloody fluid. Moreover, EVDs are employed in neurological research and clinical trials, where they assist in studying intracranial pressure dynamics and the effects of various treatments on CSF flow and brain function. This application supports advancements in medical research and the development of new therapeutic strategies. Overall, the segmentation of the EVD market by application highlights its critical role in both acute and post-operative care, underscoring its importance in enhancing pati